tclsh(1)                                      Tcl Applications                                      tclsh(1)

____________________________________________________________________________________________________________

[1mNAME[0m
       tclsh - Simple shell containing Tcl interpreter

[1mSYNOPSIS[0m
       [1mtclsh[0m ?[1m-encoding[0m [4mname[24m? ?[4mfileName[24m [4marg[24m [4marg[24m [4m...[24m?
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________

[1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       [1mTclsh[0m  is a shell-like application that reads Tcl commands from its standard input or from a file and
       evaluates them.  If invoked with no arguments then it runs interactively, reading Tcl  commands  from
       standard input and printing command results and error messages to standard output.  It runs until the
       [1mexit[0m command is invoked or until it reaches end-of-file on its standard input.   If  there  exists  a
       file  [1m.tclshrc[0m  (or [1mtclshrc.tcl[0m on the Windows platforms) in the home directory of the user, interac‐
       tive [1mtclsh[0m evaluates the file as a Tcl script just before reading the  first  command  from  standard
       input.

[1mSCRIPT[0m [1mFILES[0m
       If  [1mtclsh[0m  is  invoked with arguments then the first few arguments specify the name of a script file,
       and, optionally, the encoding of the text data stored in that script file. Any  additional  arguments
       are made available to the script as variables (see below).  Instead of reading commands from standard
       input [1mtclsh[0m will read Tcl commands from the named file;  [1mtclsh[0m will exit when it reaches the  end  of
       the  file.   The  end  of  the file may be marked either by the physical end of the medium, or by the
       character, “\032” (“\u001a”, control-Z).  If this character is present in the file, the [1mtclsh[0m  appli‐
       cation will read text up to but not including the character.  An application that requires this char‐
       acter in the file may safely encode it as “\032”, “\x1a”, or “\u001a”; or may generate it by  use  of
[7mlines 1-31[27m[K
[K       commands  such  as [1mformat[0m or [1mbinary[0m.  There is no automatic evaluation of [1m.tclshrc[0m when the name of a
       script file is presented on the [1mtclsh[0m command line, but the script  file  can  always  [1msource[0m  it  if
       desired.

       If you create a Tcl script in a file whose first line is

              [1m#!/usr/local/bin/tclsh[0m

       then  you  can  invoke  the  script file directly from your shell if you mark the file as executable.
       This assumes that [1mtclsh[0m has been installed in the default  location  in  /usr/local/bin;   if  it  is
       installed  somewhere else then you will have to modify the above line to match.  Many UNIX systems do
       not allow the [1m#![0m line to exceed about 30 characters in length, so be sure that the  [1mtclsh[0m  executable
       can be accessed with a short file name.

       An even better approach is to start your script files with the following three lines:

              [1m#!/bin/sh[0m
              [1m#[0m [1mthe[0m [1mnext[0m [1mline[0m [1mrestarts[0m [1musing[0m [1mtclsh[0m [1m\[0m
              [1mexec[0m [1mtclsh[0m [1m"$0"[0m [1m${1+"$@"}[0m

       This  approach has three advantages over the approach in the previous paragraph.  First, the location
       of the [1mtclsh[0m binary does not have to be hard-wired into the script:  it can be anywhere in your shell
       search  path.   Second,  it  gets  around  the 30-character file name limit in the previous approach.
       Third, this approach will work even if [1mtclsh[0m is itself a shell script (this is done on  some  systems
       in order to handle multiple architectures or operating systems:  the [1mtclsh[0m script selects one of sev‐
       eral binaries to run).  The three lines cause both [1msh[0m and [1mtclsh[0m to process the script, but  the  [1mexec[0m
       is  only  executed by [1msh[0m.  [1msh[0m processes the script first;  it treats the second line as a comment and
       executes the third line.  The [1mexec[0m statement cause the shell to stop processing and instead to  start
       up  [1mtclsh[0m  to  reprocess  the entire script.  When [1mtclsh[0m starts up, it treats all three lines as com‐
[7mlines 32-60[27m[K
[K       ments, since the backslash at the end of the second line causes the third line to be treated as  part
       of the comment on the second line.

       You  should  note that it is also common practice to install tclsh with its version number as part of
       the name.  This has the advantage of allowing multiple versions of Tcl to exist on the same system at
       once,  but  also the disadvantage of making it harder to write scripts that start up uniformly across
       different versions of Tcl.

[1mVARIABLES[0m
       [1mTclsh[0m sets the following global Tcl variables in addition to those created by the Tcl library  itself
       (such as [1menv[0m, which maps environment variables such as [1mPATH[0m into Tcl):

       [1margc[0m           Contains a count of the number of [4marg[24m arguments (0 if none), not including the name of
                      the script file.

       [1margv[0m           Contains a Tcl list whose elements are the [4marg[24m arguments, in order, or an empty string
                      if there are no [4marg[24m arguments.

       [1margv0[0m          Contains  [4mfileName[24m  if  it was specified.  Otherwise, contains the name by which [1mtclsh[0m
                      was invoked.

       [1mtcl_interactive[0m
                      Contains 1 if [1mtclsh[0m is running interactively (no [4mfileName[24m was specified  and  standard
                      input is a terminal-like device), 0 otherwise.

[1mPROMPTS[0m
       When  [1mtclsh[0m  is invoked interactively it normally prompts for each command with “[1m%[0m ”.  You can change
       the prompt by setting the global variables [1mtcl_prompt1[0m  and  [1mtcl_prompt2[0m.   If  variable  [1mtcl_prompt1[0m
       exists then it must consist of a Tcl script to output a prompt;  instead of outputting a prompt [1mtclsh[0m
[7mlines 61-89[27m[K
[K       will evaluate the script in [1mtcl_prompt1[0m.  The variable [1mtcl_prompt2[0m is used in a similar  way  when  a
       newline  is  typed  but  the  current  command is not yet complete; if [1mtcl_prompt2[0m is not set then no
       prompt is output for incomplete commands.

[1mSTANDARD[0m [1mCHANNELS[0m
       See [1mTcl_StandardChannels[0m for more explanations.

[1mSEE[0m [1mALSO[0m
       auto_path(n), encoding(n), env(n), fconfigure(n)

[1mKEYWORDS[0m
       application, argument, interpreter, prompt, script file, shell
